{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645018"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:11:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:11:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18076"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18076"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.13,0.03,0.1,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76269"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10790"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18076"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61773"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5758"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25144"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26124"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76269"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department by ambulance following a severe asthma attack. She is confused, agitated, and unable to speak due to respiratory distress. Her oxygen saturation is 85% and she is using accessory muscles to breathe. Some treatment must be considered, but given her confusion and inability to speak, she is not going to be able to provide formal consent.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In these circumstances, which one of the following best describes the ethical principle that allows immediate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Advanced directive","Implied consent","Presumed consent","Substituted judgement","Therapeutic need"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherapeutic need\u003C/strong\u003E is the ethical and legal principle that allows healthcare providers to deliver necessary treatment to patients who lack capacity to consent when immediate intervention is required to prevent serious harm. In this case, the patient\u0027s severe respiratory distress, confusion, and abnormal vital signs indicate an immediate need for treatment to prevent respiratory failure.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E            \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresumed consent\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the assumption that a person would have consented to treatment if they had capacity. This principle is commonly applied in organ donation systems but is not appropriate for emergency medical treatment where the patient\u0027s current wishes are unknown.\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvanced directive\u003C/strong\u003E is a formal document prepared when a person has capacity to specify their future treatment preferences. In this emergency situation, there is no time to check for an advanced directive, and most young patients would not have one.\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstituted judgement\u003C/strong\u003E involves making decisions based on consultation with family or others who know the patient\u0027s values and preferences. In an emergency like severe asthma, delaying treatment to contact family would be dangerous and inappropriate.\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImplied consent\u003C/strong\u003E requires the patient to demonstrate through their actions that they agree to treatment. This patient\u0027s confusion and agitation mean she cannot meaningfully imply consent to treatment.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EWhen treating under therapeutic need, healthcare providers must document their assessment of the patient\u0027s lack of capacity, the immediate clinical need for intervention, and why waiting to obtain consent was not possible. Treatment should be limited to what is immediately necessary to prevent serious harm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Therapeutic need occurs when a patient requires medical intervention but lacks capacity to consent.","Healthcare providers must act in the patient\u0027s best interests when providing treatment under therapeutic need.","Documentation of therapeutic need must clearly justify why treatment was necessary without formal consent."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61773"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18076"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61773"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T17:03:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T17:05:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10790"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76269"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":